Introduction¶

To complete my Data Analysis project I will be using the European Soccer Database.

This database is a collection of 7 different tablels. It contains data of around 25,000 matches, about 10,000 players, 11 different countries with their lead championship, seasons 2008-2016, player and team attributes from the EA Sports FIFA video game, betting odds and detail of match events.

Here are the different questions I asked:

  • Which team factors correlate most with best goal differential?
  • Which team factors correlate most with most wins?
  • Which teams were the best overall (season, team)?
  • Which teams have been the best and worst consistently?

Data Cleaning¶

I began by making the match dataframe into a more of a season statistics dataset using aggregate by-season/team. I performed further cleaning on the match dataframe and added my own season statistics.

The team attributes already is aggregated by season and team, so I basically did some cleaing on it. Then I merged the 2 datasets in to one big dataset, which I performed exploratory analysis on.

The only place we can see teams is home team and away team columns. In order to make calculations easier, I aggregated the dataframe by home team and season. Then I aggregated once again on away team and season. I will later combine the home dataframe and the away dataframe for further analysis.

In [5]:
#matched data so that it would match team_attr dataframe
match['date'] = match['season'].str.slice_replace(start=4, repl='')
#incorporated the team dataframe into match dataframe because team only has 2 columns
team_dict = dict(zip(team['team_api_id'], team['team']))
match['home_team'] = [ team_dict[id_] for id_ in match['home_team_api_id'] ]
match['away_team'] = [ team_dict[id_] for id_ in match['away_team_api_id'] ]
#Created 3 different columns to represent win, ties and loses
match['home_win'] = (match['home_team_goal'] >  match['away_team_goal'])
match['tie'] = (match['home_team_goal'] ==  match['away_team_goal'])
match['away_win'] = (match['home_team_goal'] <  match['away_team_goal'])
#crated 2 dataframes with home matchs and away matches, both with same set of columns
home_match = match[['date', 'home_team', 'home_win', 'tie', 'away_win', 'home_team_goal', 'away_team_goal']] 
home_match.columns = ['date', 'team', 'wins', 'ties', 'loses', 'goals_scored', 'goals_given']
away_match = match[['date', 'away_team', 'away_win', 'tie', 'home_win', 'away_team_goal', 'home_team_goal']]
away_match.columns = home_match.columns
#get aggregated statistics of home and away matches
home_match = home_match.groupby(by=["team", 'date'], as_index=False).sum()
away_match = away_match.groupby(by=["team", 'date'], as_index=False).sum()
home_match.shape, away_match.shape

Here I merged the home and away dataframe. Following the merge, I created my own columns showing statistics that were not displayed earlier.

In [6]:
df = home_match.merge(away_match, on=["team", 'date'])
new_labels = []
for col in df.columns:
    if '_x' in col:
        new_labels.append('home_' + col[:-2])  
    elif '_y' in col:
        new_labels.append('away_' + col[:-2]) 
    else :
        new_labels.append(col)
df.columns = new_labels
df['wins'] = df['home_wins'] + df['away_wins']
df['loses'] = df['home_loses'] + df['away_loses']
df['ties'] = df['home_ties'] + df['away_ties']
df['goals_differential'] = (df['home_goals_scored'] + df['away_goals_scored']) / (df['home_goals_given'] + df['away_goals_given'])

df['games'] = (df['wins'] + df['loses'] + df['ties'])
df['win_pct'] = df['wins'] / df['games']
df['loss_pct'] = df['loses'] / df['games']
df['ties_pct'] = df['ties'] / df['games']
df.head()

It seems like whether the Buildup Play Position and Chance Creation Positioning was free-form or organized had the biggest impact on the goal differential. To account for teams that played more or less games, I used goal differential which was the ratio (goals scored/goals given).

Here I showed a box-plot of the 4 different situaions. The blue line going across the middle is the mean goal differential. As we can see Free Form's mean is above the total mean, while Organized is below for both. Organized vs free-form creation positioning means that that in any given time how much freedom people have the flexibility to stray from positions to support other positions on offense (meaning the "third pitch" of the field. Organized vs free-form build-play-position is similar in that it indicates people's flexibility to stray from their position in the "first two pitches" of the field meaning around midfield.

In [14]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
cols = ['chanceCreationPositioningClass_Free Form', 'chanceCreationPositioningClass_Organised',
        'buildUpPlayPositioningClass_Free Form', 'buildUpPlayPositioningClass_Organised']
labels = ['Free Form Creation-Positioning', 'Organized Creation-Positioning', 
          'Free Form Buildup-Play-Positioning', 'Organized Buildup-Play-Positioning']
factor = 'goals_differential'
ylab = 'Goal Differential'
ylim = 3
def boxplot_() :
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(18, 20))
    i = 1
    m = df[factor].mean()
    for col in cols :
        x = df[ df[col] == 1 ][[factor]]
        ax = plt.subplot(2, 2, i);
        ax.boxplot(x[factor]);
        plt.ylim(0, ylim);
        ax.set_xlabel(labels[i - 1])
        ax.set_ylabel(ylab)
        ax.set_title(ylab +' vs ' + labels[i - 1]);
        plt.axhline(y=m)
        i += 1
boxplot_()

The blue line indicated the mean goal differential of all teams. The orange line is the mean goal differential of the distribution.

As indicated by the 4 boxplots for free-form for both creation-position and build-up position was mostly above the blue line which was the mean goal differential.

On the other hand, the distribution for organized for both creation-position and build-up position was mostly below the blue line which was the mean goal differential.

In [15]:
ylab = 'Goal Differential'
factor = 'goals_differential'

def barplot_() :
    df_temp = df[['chanceCreationPositioningClass_Free Form', 'chanceCreationPositioningClass_Organised',
                  'buildUpPlayPositioningClass_Free Form', 'buildUpPlayPositioningClass_Organised', factor]]

    create_free = df_temp[df_temp["chanceCreationPositioningClass_Free Form"] == 1][factor].mean()
    create_organized = df_temp[df_temp["chanceCreationPositioningClass_Organised"] == 1][factor].mean()
    build_free = df_temp[df_temp['buildUpPlayPositioningClass_Free Form'] == 1][factor].mean()
    build_organized = df_temp[df_temp['buildUpPlayPositioningClass_Organised'] == 1][factor].mean()


    m = df[factor].mean()
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))

    ax = plt.subplot(1, 2, 1);
    ax.bar(['Free Form Creation-Positioning', 'Organized Creation-Positioning'], [create_free, create_organized]);
    ax.axhline(y=m, color='orange');
    plt.axhline(y=m, color='orange')
    ax.set_ylabel(ylab);
    ax.set_title(ylab +' vs Creation-Positioning Style');

    ax = plt.subplot(1, 2, 2);
    ax.bar(['Free Form Buildup-Play-Positioning', 'Organized Buildup-Play-Positioning'], [build_free, build_organized]);
    plt.axhline(y=m, color='orange');
    ax.set_ylabel(ylab);
    ax.set_title(ylab +' vs Buildup-Positioning Style');
barplot_()

To more concisely show this difference in means for free form and organized. In both cases the taller bar is the mean goal differential of the free-form position, the shorter is organized and the orange line is the organized mean goal differential.

Note on Research Question 1 and 2¶

As we can see from the box plots and bar plots for creation-postioning and building-position there is a correlation between free form and better win percentage/goal differential. However, we saw that neither of these correlation coffecients were actually very high. All were below 0.3, meaning we cannot say for sure whether these metrics had a significant impact on goal differential or win percentage.

This can also said about defensive pressure. The 2 scatterplots barely showed any correlation between defensive pressure and win percentage/goal differential.

Basically, correlation does not mean causation. There are many factors that affect goal differential and win percentage, meaning there are many confounding variables.

One thing I did want to see was how common teams had free form vs organized.

Research Question 4: Which teams have been the best and worst consistently?¶

Here I aggregate the teams by win percentage and number of seasons participated. My definition of consistent is atleast 4 out of the 6 possible seasons. As a result, I did not count teams that played 4 or less seasons.

df_agg.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
df_agg = df_agg.query("count > 4")

Conclusions¶

My first question I asked were which factors affected goal differential the most. I began by doing the correlation matrix. Using a correlation matrix which took the Pearsons Constant, I found that 3 factors (Free Form Creation Positioning, Free Form Buildup Positioning, and defensive pressure) had a weak positive correlation of 0.2+. I also saw that there were 2 factors (Organized Creation Positioning and Organized Buildup Positioning) had a weak negative correlation of 0.2+. I visualized those 5 factors using box-plots and scatterplot.

The second question I asked was which factors affected win percentage the most. Uninterestingly I found those same 3 factors with a weak positive correlation and same 2 factors with a weak negative correlation and did very similar visualizations.

In the end, I concluded that the type of positioning had the most correlation with goal differential and win percentage. Free form is supposedly better and organized is worse. Defensive pressure is also correlated with both. However, the reason why these results are not conclusive because all 3 are weak correlations and correlation does not equal causation. Furthermore, we can see from the 'Note on Research Question 1 and 2 section that most teams use Organized Creation-Positioning so the sample sizes are skewed.

The third question I asked was which teams were the best overall (team, season). The top 5 best performances were the 2010 FC Porto, 2013 Juventus, 2012 FC Bayern Munich, 2014 PSV and FC Bayern Munich. The bottom 5 worst performances were 2014 Crdoba CF, 2015 Aston Villa, 2015 ES Troyes AC, 2010 AC Arles-Avignon, and 2010 Willem II. These ranks were generated purely by win percentage.

The last question I asked was which teams were the best and worst consistently. These ranks were generated purely by average win percentage. The top 5 best teams were FC Barcelona, SL Benifica, Real Madrid CF, FC Porto, and FC Bayern Munich. The bottom 5 worst teams were Acadmica de Coimbra, Aston Villa, St. Mirren, Vitria Setbal, Sunderland. I also made sure that in those 6 season these were teams that had been consistently competing, meaning they competed in at least 4 out of 6.

Not for all all 4 research questions these were conducted between the timeline of 2010-2016.
